  "prompt": "What is Technical Resignation?",
  "response": "Technical Resignation is a term used in employment contexts that refers to a situation where an employee is effectively forced to resign from their job, often due to unfavorable or intolerable working conditions, but without being formally terminated or laid off. Here are some key characteristics:\n\n1. Characteristics:\n- Employee feels compelled to quit\n- Working conditions have become unbearable\n- Employer creates an environment that makes staying impossible\n- Subtle pressure or manipulation to make the employee leave\n\n2. Common Scenarios:\n- Significant reduction in responsibilities\n- Demotion without official communication\n- Hostile work environment\n- Repeated workplace harassment\n- Unreasonable performance expectations\n- Deliberate isolation or exclusion\n\n3. Employer Motivations:\n- Avoid paying severance or unemployment benefits\n- Prevent potential legal complications of formal termination\n- Pressure an employee to leave voluntarily\n\n4. Employee Implications:\n- May impact future job prospects\n- Potential financial uncertainty\n- Psychological stress\n- Potential challenge in claiming unemployment benefits\n\n5. Legal Considerations:\n- Can sometimes be considered constructive dismissal\n- Might provide grounds for wrongful resignation claims\n- Depends on specific workplace circumstances and jurisdictions\n\nTechnical resignation is a subtle form of workplace manipulation that can significantly impact an employee's professional and personal life.",
